    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="555"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d555">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 <gloss target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>/9–143:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Campbell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">British Foreign
                            Office</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d555fn1">Printed from a copy made available to the
                        Department of State on September 1, 1943, by the British Embassy at
                        Washington.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-30">August 30,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Same source in Italian Legation<note n="2" xml:id="d555fn2">Not identified in the
                        source text. Earlier information with reference to the Italian peace feelers
                        had been passed to the British Embassy at Lisbon by Raimondo Manzini,
                        Secretary of the Italian Legation there. See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_1056">p. 1056</ref>.</note> has now reported that news
                    has been received that General C.<note n="3" xml:id="d555fn3">Giuseppe
                        Castellano.</note> duly arrived at his destination.</p>
                <pb facs="1305" n="1191" xml:id="pg_1191"/>
                <list>
                    <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                    <item>If there has still been no contact with Algiers by <gloss target="#t_WT1"
                            >W/T</gloss>, this may be due either to <list>
                            <label>(1)</label>
                            <item>Signor M.<note n="4" xml:id="d555fn4">Franco Montanari.</note>
                                having forgotten his instructions.</item>
                            <label>(2)</label>
                            <item>To his having been caught by Germans en route, if it was he who
                                was going to take charge of the Instrument [of Surrender?],
                                or</item>
                            <label>(3)</label>
                            <item>To Italian Legation having telegraphed to Rome at General Z.’s
                                instance to suggest withholding of reply until receipt of long
                                    terms.<note n="5" xml:id="d555fn5">The “long” or “comprehensive”
                                    terms of surrender had been given to General Giacomo Zanussi at
                                    Lisbon on August 27, 1943. See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                                        target="#pg_1181">p. 1181</ref>, fn. 3, and <ref
                                        target="#pg_1184">p. 1184</ref>, fn. 13.</note>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
